      <li class="ctsh clearfix" data-cid="29613410">
        <div class="ilst">
          <a href="https://www.douban.com/people/28748505/"><img src="https://img3.doubanio.com/icon/u28748505-13.jpg" alt="Iris" class="" /></a>
        </div>
        <div class="con">
          <div class="nlst">
            <h3>
              <div class="note-toggle rr">
                <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/29613410/" class="note-unfolder">展开</a>
                <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="note-folder">收起</a>
              </div>
              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/29613410/" class="">The Elementary Forms of Religious Life</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/28748505/" class=" " title="Iris">Iris</a>
                (越是一个人，越要像模像样地生活)
              
                <span class="allstar40" title="推荐"></span>
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="29613410">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">In Durkheimâ&euro;&trade;s The Elementary Forms of Religious Life, he again conducted his research following the rules he made for sociological research, which is making definition first, then refuting former explanations and at last demonstrating his own understanding of the subject he studied.

According to Durkheim, sociology â&euro;&oelig;pursues knowledge of the earlier forms of civilization not only to know them ...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2013-12-04 05:13</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                In Durkheim’s The Elementary Forms of Religious Life, he again conducted his research following the rules he made for sociological research, which is making definition first, then refuting former explanations and at last demonstrating his own understanding of the subject he studied.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>According to Durkheim, sociology “pursues knowledge of the earlier forms of civilization not only to know them and reconstruct them, but, like all positive science, its goal is first and foremost to explain a current reality, something close to us and consequently capable of affecting our ideas and actions. This reality is man, more specifically is man today.” (Pp.3) Religion, in Durkheim’s eyes, is such a kind of social reality/fact. By focusing on the primitive and simplest form of religion, he implied that “religion is something eminently social.” (Pp.11) There is nothing different between religion and science, both of which were all products of society.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>In this book, Durkheim defines religion in this way: a religion is a unified system of beliefs and practices relative to sacred things, that is to say, things set apart and surrounded by prohibitions-beliefs and practices that unite its adherents in a single moral community called a church. (Pp.46) Durkheim to some extent borrowed Darwin’s idea of evolution. In his mind, by doing research into totemism, the simplest kind of religion, we could reach the very nature of religion itself, which could as well be applied to all other kinds of religion. Therefore, Durkheim chose tribes in Australia as his subject. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Unlike his predecessors, when talking about the origin of religion, Durkheim looked to the corroboree in Austrilia instead of referring to people’s inner psychology. He noticed that “it is in this effervescent social settings, and from this very effervescence, that religious idea seems to be born. And this origin seems confirmed by the fact that in Australia, strictly religious activity is almost entirely concentrated in time when these assemblies are held.” (Pp. 164) Assemblies put people in a state of exaltation and under this condition, people was “possessed and led by some external power that makes him think and act differently from normal terms”, and this was the origin of religion. By analyzing the origin of religion, Durkheim intended to reveal that society greatly shaped and formed individuals’ consciousness, whether admitted it or not. Individual’s consciousness always was restrained by societal one. Therefore, Durkheim concluded that the value of collectiveness for human being, lied not in satisfying people’s physical needs but in providing them ethical and moral systems which can help them get rid of their animal nature and turned into a real member of human society.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>What I find interesting about this book is the role Durkheim assigned to religion. According to him, religion is a necessity in maintaining the whole social system. In other words, religion is rather a prerequisite for society than a part of it, which in my opinion, is quite problematic in that it reversed the position of religion and society. Marx as well talked about religion. According to Marx, every religion was related with particular socio-historical background and it can only be treated as a social product during certain social phases, which will finally disappear with the development of human society. Besides, if Durkheim is right, how would he analyze societies like China where there was no national religion?

                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







